{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 06:31:23.969597", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nScope and intent\\n- Detect anomalies, localize faulty devices if any, and identify root cause(s) based on observed state and active tests.\\n- No remediation proposed.\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Overall network health is good. OSPF adjacencies are up, routes are present end-to-end, hosts have working DHCP configuration, DNS resolves local names, and HTTP services (Apache frontends and the Nginx load balancer) are reachable with low latencies and zero packet loss in tested paths.\\n- Backend isolation appears intact (no backend network leaked into OSPF; backends are not visible/reachable from user subnets).\\n- No functional anomalies detected. Minor jitter spikes were observed in a small number of ICMP samples but without loss, and not indicative of a fault.\\n\\nKey observations and evidence\\n\\n1) Host IP/DHCP and default routing\\n- host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.24/24 via DHCP with default route via 10.1.1.1.\\n- host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.22/24 via DHCP with default route via 10.2.1.1.\\n- Both show dynamic leases and valid defaults, indicating functioning access L2 and DHCP relay/path.\\n\\n2) Layer-3 reachability (broad ping sweep)\\n- Extensive cross-subnet ICMP probing shows 0% packet loss across tested pairs (get_reachability). RTTs are low (generally ~1–5 ms) across areas, consistent with a healthy routed core/distribution/access hierarchy.\\n\\n3) Server farm reachability and HTTP service\\n- From host_1_1_1_1 to web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): 0% loss, RTT ~1.9–11.9 ms (occasional jitter spike).\\n- HTTP timing from host_1_1_1_1:\\n  - http://web99.local (Nginx LB): DNS lookup ~3–6 ms; connect ~5–9 ms; TTFB ~0.21–0.25 s; total ~1.02–1.05 s.\\n  - http://web0.local (Apache frontend): DNS lookup ~4–49 ms; connect ~5–51 ms; TTFB ~0.23–0.39 s; total ~1.03–1.19 s.\\n- Netstat on web servers (web_server_0..3) and load_balancer shows 0.0.0.0:80 listening as expected; DNS server listening on 10.200.0.2:53 (and loopback), consistent with design.\\n\\n4) OSPF adjacencies and routing tables\\n- server_access_router:\\n  - OSPF neighbor full with 172.16.0.3 over eth7; 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected (br0) and advertised; all user subnets 10.1.x.0/24 and 10.2.x.0/24 learned via eth7.\\n- router_dist_1_1:\\n  - 10.1.1.0/24 directly connected; 10.200.0.0/24 and other subnets learned via core (172.16.0.6).\\n- router_core_1:\\n  - Multiple OSPF neighbors full; routes to 10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.3 (to core_3), 10.2.x.0/24 via 172.16.0.1, and 10.1.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.7.\\n  - ECMP seen for a point-to-point link (172.16.0.4/31) – normal behavior in a meshed core.\\n\\n5) Backend isolation (as per design)\\n- The only server farm network visible in OSPF is 10.200.0.0/24. The dedicated backend segment (load_balancer:eth1 to backend_web_0) is not present in the OSPF route tables, and backend hosts are not discoverable in the reachability inventory. This indicates the backend network is not leaked into the routed domain, aligning with the requirement that backends not be directly accessible from user hosts.\\n\\nAnomalies detected\\n- None functionally significant:\\n  - Sporadic RTT jitter to 10.200.0.3 (max ~11.9 ms) without loss. This is minor and not symptomatic of a routing or reachability fault.\\n  - Slight variability in HTTP timing; TTFB and totals are within expected ranges for a small lab and do not suggest systemic issues.\\n\\nLocalization and root cause\\n- No faults localized. All tested components (access switches implicitly via successful DHCP and L2, distribution and core routers via OSPF neighbor and route state, server_access_router, DNS, web servers, load balancer) are operating normally.\\n- Backend isolation is preserved by routing policy (non-advertised backend subnet) as evidenced by OSPF route tables; therefore, no policy leak root cause exists.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The network is healthy: OSPF adjacencies are stable, routes are correct, DHCP and DNS services are reachable, and HTTP services (frontends and LB) work end-to-end from user hosts. Backend web servers are not exposed to user subnets as intended. No actionable anomalies identified., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='330e5cfe-9668-4553-b50c-59dd2221427a'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
